{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Following BERT's breakthrough, many alternative neural language models (e.g.",
    "XLNet, RoBERTa, ELECTRA) have been developed that use different architectures, hyperparameter tuning, pre-training objectives, and additional training data [36][37][38].",
    "Since the pretraining of these language models does not require labelled data, there has been a trend of training increasingly large models using more and more massive unlabelled corpora.",
    "These large language models (LLMs) push computational boundaries through a mix of new neural architectures and sheer increases in size (number of parameters, size of vocabulary, number of learned vectors, all reflecting a large amount of pre-training literature) [33,39,40].",
    "LLMs pre-trained on vast amounts of text often serve as foundation models that can be adapted to a wide range of downstream tasks through additional supervised learning with smaller datasets (Zhou et al. 2023) (see section Transfer learning: adapting language models for ecology & evolution)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "XLNet, RoBERTa, ELECTRA) have been developed that use different architectures, hyperparameter tuning, pre-training objectives, and additional training data [36][37][38].",
    "These large language models (LLMs) push computational boundaries through a mix of new neural architectures and sheer increases in size (number of parameters, size of vocabulary, number of learned vectors, all reflecting a large amount of pre-training literature) [33,39,40]."
  ]
